<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900501-0009</DOCNO><DOCID>900501-0009.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>05/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   MOSLEM MILITANTS FREED an American captive, the second ineight days.   Kidnappers in Beirut, putting pressure on Bush toreciprocate with a goodwill gesture toward Iran, releasedFrank Reed, who had been held since September 1986. The57-year-old educator, who called his captivity &quot;lonely&quot; and&quot;boring,&quot; headed to West Germany after a stop in Syria.Robert Polhill, freed April 22, delivered a message from hiscaptors to Bush, who hailed Reed's release and thanked Iranand Syria. The president also said he'd have &quot;no objection&quot;if Israel frees a Shiite Moslem cleric, as Tehran hasdemanded.</LP><TEXT>   The State Department issued its annual report onterrorism, which accused Iran of being the &quot;most active statesponsor&quot; of terrorism last year.   ---   A former HUD official told a congressional panel that thehousing agency under Secretary Pierce operated &quot;basically onpolitical favoritism.&quot; DuBois Gilliam, once a deputyassistant secretary who currently is serving an 18-monthprison term for bribery, said Pierce personally madedecisions on project approvals.   ---   NASA engineers untangled a cable on one of the HubbleSpace Telescope's main antennas, a move that could allow atleast limited operation of the orbiting device. Groundcontrollers hadn't been able to communicate with thetelescope since its launch Wednesday by the space shuttleDiscovery.   ---   A House Democratic task force said El Salvador's inquiryinto last year's killings of six Jesuit priests has come to&quot;a virtual standstill.&quot; The report, which questioned whetherfull justice would be done, is expected to influence effortsto reduce aid to the government of President Cristiani.   ---   A citizens' group in Latvia demanded that the Balticrepublic emulate Lithuania and proclaim its independence fromthe Soviet Union. The group, claiming to represent hundredsof thousands of Latvians, termed the republic &quot;an occupiedcountry.&quot; The call came as the legislature prepared to meetthis week to discuss secession.                                                                                                          About 20,000 Lithuanians gathered to mourn a man whoburned himself to death in Moscow last week to protest theKremlin's efforts to end the republic's independence bid.Officials in Vilnius, meanwhile, were quoted as saying therepublic was prepared to suspend its secession drive ifMoscow agrees to open negotiations.   ---   West German leaders attempted to overcome Kremlinopposition to a united Germany's membership in NATO, sayingBonn wouldn't overlook the Soviet Union's &quot;justified securityinterests.&quot; The assurances came as the two Germanys and thefour World War II victors prepared to open unificationnegotiations Saturday in Bonn.   ---   South Korean riot police stormed the headquarters of theKorean Broadcasting System in Seoul, crushing 19 days ofdemonstrations by workers that have disrupted state radio andtelevision networks. In the southeastern city of Ulsan,shipyard workers clashed with riot police for a third day,and labor unrest spread across the nation.   ---   Bush conferred in Washington with Panama's PresidentEndara and announced the nomination of the first-everPanamanian to manage the Panama Canal. The president, whohadn't met with Endara since the U.S. invasion of Panama lastDecember, also chastised Congress for moving slowly on aidfor the Central American nation.   ---   The EPA will issue rules aimed at reducing the amount ofdioxin that gets into water and soil through the making ofbleached paper. The agency said, however, that the risk posedby dioxin in paper products is &quot;no cause for alarm,&quot; andreferred this area to the FDA.   ---   The Supreme Court let stand a ruling by a federal appealscourt in New York that abortion-rights groups lack standingto challenge the tax-exempt status of the Roman CatholicChurch. The justices also let stand a lower-court ruling thatallows random drug testing of Transportation Departmentemployees who have safety-related jobs.   ---   Israel's Herzog called for changes in the nation'selectoral system and criticized politicians for showing a&quot;total contempt for the principles of democracy.&quot; Thepresident's Independence Day address came amid politicaldivisions that have blocked formation of a coalitionfollowing the March 15 collapse of Prime Minister Shamir'sgovernment.   ---   South Africa's foreign minister said the country's blackscouldn't push the white minority too far without risking abacklash that could destroy the nation. His remarks came asthe Pretoria government and the African National Congressprepared for discussions this week aimed at exploring thepossibility of black-white power-sharing.   ---   Authorities in China announced the lifting of martial lawin Tibet's capital. The move came nearly 14 months after therestrictions were imposed in Lhasa to quell three days ofnationalist rioting that left at least 16 people dead andmore than 100 injured.   ---   The U.S. resumed diplomatic relations with the Marxistgovernment of South Yemen after a break of nearly 21 years.The country has had close ties with the Soviet Union. Inannouncing the move, the State Department said Aden has begunliberalizing its economy and political system.</TEXT></DOC>